shwords.com/books/view/38962 Harem Novel From Asl\u0131 Sancar]\n* {{Cite AmCyc |last=Godwin |first=Parke |authorlink=Parke Godwin (journalist) |wstitle=Harem |short=x}}\n{{Islamic architecture}}\n{{Room}}\n\n[[Category:Arab culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic architectural elements]]\n[[Category:Islamic culture]]\n[[Category:Harem| ]]\n[[Category:Ottoman culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic terminology]]\n[[Category:Women's quarters]]\n[[Category:Rooms]]\n", "name_user": "173.48.32.107", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Yes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harem"}
{"title_page": "Treaty of Paris (1810)", "text_new": "{{For|other treaties of Paris|Treaty of Paris (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name                 = Treaty of Paris\n| long_name            = \n| image                = \n| image_width          = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| type                 = Bilateral treaty\n| context              = \n| date_drafted         = \n| date_signed          = {{Start date|df=yes|1810|1|6}}\n| location_signed      = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic|France]]\n| date_sealed          = \n| date_effective       = \n| condition_effective  = \n| date_expiration      = \n| date_expiry          = \n| mediators            = \n| negotiators          = \n| original_signatories = [[First French Empire|France]]<br/>[[Sweden]]\n| signatories          = \n| parties              = \n| ratifiers            = France<br/>Sweden\n| depositor            = \n| depositories         = \n| citations            = \n| language             = \n| languages            = \n| wikisource           = \n| wikisource1          =\n| footnotes            =\n}}\nThe '''Treaty of Paris''', signed on 6 January 1810, ended the [[First War against Napoleon|war]] between [[France]] and [[Sweden]] after Sweden's defeat by [[Russia]], an ally of France, in the [[Finnish War]] of 1808\u20131809.  \n\n==History==\nRussia had previously been an ally of Sweden in the [[War of the Third Coalition|Third]] and [[War of the Fourth Coalition|Fourth]] Coalitions against France, but after Russia's defeat at [[Battle of Friedland|Friedland]], she joined France and attacked Sweden so as to compel her to join [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon's]] [[Continental System]]. The primary result of the treaty was Sweden's agreement to join the Continental System, so that Sweden would not trade with the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>Durant, Will. The Age of Napoleon. New York: MJF Books, 1975. pg. 236.</ref>  \n\nShortly after the treaty was signed, on 21 August 1810, one of Napoleon's marshals, [[Charles XIV of Sweden|Jean-Baptiste Bernadotte]], was elected crown prince of Sweden, and he went on to found the [[House of Bernadotte]], which remains the [[Royal House]] of Sweden.  The peace resulting from the treaty lasted until Napoleon's refusal to permit Sweden to annex [[Norway]], which was then under the sovereignty of [[Denmark]], an ally of France.<ref name=\"Durant, pg. 663\">Durant, pg. 663.</ref>  This was followed in January 1812 by French occupation of [[Swedish Pomerania]] for violation of the Continental System, since Sweden was still trading with the United Kingdom. In April 1812, Sweden signed  the [[Treaty of Saint Petersburg (1812)|Treaty of Petersburg]] with Russia against France.<ref name=\"Durant, pg. 663\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Napoleonic Wars]]\n*[[First War against Napoleon]]\n*[[Second War against Napoleon]]\n*[[Treaty of Paris (1814)]]\n*[[Treaty of Paris (1815)]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n==Related reading==\n* Will Durant, Ariel Durant (1975) ''The Age of Napoleon'' (Simon and Schuster) {{ISBN|9781451647686}}\n*Ulf Sundberg (1997) ''Svenska freder och stillest\u00e5nd 1249-1814'' (Hjalmarson & H\u00f6gberg) {{ISBN|978-9189080010}}\n[[Category:Napoleonic Wars treaties|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of France|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of Sweden|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the First French Empire|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:1810 in France]]\n[[Category:1810 treaties]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Sweden relations]]\n[[Category:1810 in Sweden]]\n[[Category:January 1810 events]]\n[[Category:1810s in Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other treaties of Paris|Treaty of Paris (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name                 = Treaty of Paris\n| long_name            = \n| image                = \n| image_width          = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| type                 = bilateral treaty\n| context              = \n| date_drafted         = \n| date_signed          = {{Start date|df=yes|1810|1|6}}\n| location_signed      = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic|France]]\n| date_sealed          = \n| date_effective       = \n| condition_effective  = \n| date_expiration      = \n| date_expiry          = \n| mediators            = \n| negotiators          = \n| original_signatories = [[First French Empire|France]]<br/>[[Sweden]]\n| signatories          = \n| parties              = \n| ratifiers            = France<br/>Sweden\n| depositor            = \n| depositories         = \n| citations            = \n| language             = \n| languages            = \n| wikisource           = \n| wikisource1          =\n| footnotes            =\n}}\nThe '''Treaty of Paris''', signed on 6 January 1810, ended the [[First War against Napoleon|war]] between [[France]] and [[Sweden]] after Sweden's defeat by [[Russia]], an ally of France, in the [[Finnish War]] of 1808\u20131809.  \n\n==History==\nRussia had previously been an ally of Sweden in the [[War of the Third Coalition|Third]] and [[War of the Fourth Coalition|Fourth]] Coalitions against France, but after Russia's defeat at [[Battle of Friedland|Friedland]], she joined France and attacked Sweden so as to compel her to join [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon's]] [[Continental System]]. The primary result of the treaty was Sweden's agreement to join the Continental System, so that Sweden would not trade with the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>Durant, Will. The Age of Napoleon. New York: MJF Books, 1975. pg. 236.</ref>  \n\nShortly after the treaty was signed, on 21 August 1810, one of Napoleon's marshals, [[Charles XIV of Sweden|Jean-Baptiste Bernadotte]], was elected crown prince of Sweden, and he went on to found the [[House of Bernadotte]], which remains the [[Royal House]] of Sweden.  The peace resulting from the treaty lasted until Napoleon's refusal to permit Sweden to annex [[Norway]], which was then under the sovereignty of [[Denmark]], an ally of France.<ref name=\"Durant, pg. 663\">Durant, pg. 663.</ref>  This was followed in January 1812 by French occupation of [[Swedish Pomerania]] for violation of the Continental System, since Sweden was still trading with the United Kingdom. In April 1812, Sweden signed  the [[Treaty of Saint Petersburg (1812)|Treaty of Petersburg]] with Russia against France.<ref name=\"Durant, pg. 663\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Napoleonic Wars]]\n*[[First War against Napoleon]]\n*[[Second War against Napoleon]]\n*[[Treaty of Paris (1814)]]\n*[[Treaty of Paris (1815)]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n==Related reading==\n* Will Durant, Ariel Durant (1975) ''The Age of Napoleon'' (Simon and Schuster) {{ISBN|9781451647686}}\n*Ulf Sundberg (1997) ''Svenska freder och stillest\u00e5nd 1249-1814'' (Hjalmarson & H\u00f6gberg) {{ISBN|978-9189080010}}\n[[Category:Napoleonic Wars treaties|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of France|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of Sweden|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the First French Empire|Paris (1810)]]\n[[Category:1810 in France]]\n[[Category:1810 treaties]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Sweden relations]]\n[[Category:1810 in Sweden]]\n[[Category:January 1810 events]]\n[[Category:1810s in Paris]]\n", "name_user": "EmilHenriksson61", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1810)"}
